eson, vc, mc -- tCitations for the Award of the Distinguished Service Order -- tCitations for the Award of the Military Cross -- tCitations for the Award of the Distinguished Conduct Medal -- tRecommendations for the Award of the Military Medal -- tMilitary Offences in 11th Brigade -- tCourts-Martial Record -- tCommanding Officers 1915–1939 -- tRegimental Sergeants-Major 1915–1939 -- tRegimental Choruses of the 9th Mississauga Horse and the 75th (Mississauga) Battalion -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tCanadian Unit, Formation, and Command Histories series0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aForeword by His Royal Highness Charles, Prince of Wales Hospital ships filled the harbour of Le Havre as the 75th Mississauga Battalion arrived on 13 August 1916. Those soldiers who survived would spend almost three years in a tiny corner of northeastern France and northwestern Belgium (Flanders), where many of their comrades still lie. And they would serve in many of the most horrific battles of that long, bloody conflict—Saint Eloi, the Somme, Arras, Vimy, Hill 70, Lens, Passchendaele, Amiens, Drocourt-Quéant, Canal du Nord, Cambrai, and Valenciennes. This book tells the story of the 75th Battalion (later the Toronto Scottish Regiment) and the five thousand men who formed it—most from Toronto—from all walks of life. They included professionals, university graduates, white- and blue-collar workers, labourers, and the unemployed, some illiterate. They left a comfortable existence in the prosperous, strongly pro-British provincial capital for life in the trenches of France and Flanders. Tommy Church, mayor of Toronto from 1915 to 1921, sought to include his city’s name in the unit’s name because of the many city officials and local residents who served in it. Three years later Church accepted the 75th’s now heavily emblazoned colours for safekeeping at City Hall from Lieutenant-Colonel Colin Harbottle, who returned with his bloodied but successful survivors. The author pulls no punches in recounting their labours, triumphs, and travails. Timothy J. Stewart undertook exhaustive research for this first-ever history of the 75th, drawing from archival sources (focusing on critical decisions by Brigadier Victor Oldum, General Officer Commanding 11th Brigade), diaries, letters, newspaper accounts, and interviews.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aHistory: Canadian History. 4aHistory: Military History. 7aHISTORY / Military / Canada.2bisacsh  a75th Battalion.  aBelgium.  aCambrai.  aCanada.  aCanadians.  aCavalry.  aFrance.  aGreat Britain.  aGreat War.  aInfantry.  aMississauga.  aPasschendaele.  aPrince Charles.  aQueen Elizabeth.  aQueen Mother.  aRemembrance.  aSomme.  aToronto Scottish Regiment.  aToronto.  aUniversity of Toronto.  aVimy.  aWW I.  aWar to end all Wars.  aWestern Front.  aWorld War I.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619940uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978177112183540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781771121835423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781771121835/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles